  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Irrigation package for sand rivers</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022;	Short general project overviewAgricultural production by small-scale farmers in most of Mozambique is sub-optimal, mainly due to water shortages. In the absence of irrigation dry spells frequently lead to crop failure interrupting food supply chains. The quantity and quality of the products are below standards and there are limited to no opportunities for realizing an extra crop in the dry season. The slightly larger farms that have conventional diesel pumps spend huge amounts on fuel and still do not have water when the river is dry.The irrigation package for sand rivers allows small-scale farmers to abstract water from a new source, i.e. the shallow aquifer of the sandy bed of seasonal rivers (in this case the Limpopo). This water can be efficiently extracted and conducted to the fields and applied by using efficient irrigation techniques such as drip irrigation. The smallholders and their user associations profit directly from the package. Indirectly also the Southern region water management authority ARA-Sul who should ensure efficient and sustainable use of the water source can profit from the approach. The same applies for the dealer network that will sell and maintain the package, and the city dwellers benefiting from improved food security.&#x2022;	Initial activities and results of the projectThe purpose of this feasibility study is to identify the main strengths, weaknesses, challenges and opportunities of the package. Hence, it aims to:1. validate the technical specifications of the &#x2018;irrigation package for sand rivers&#x2019; in light of the socio-economic and biophysical context through technical assessments and installation of the package at three experimental sites;2. assess the costs, benefits, and impact of the technique (including volumes of water, crop types, added value of irrigation, also in monetary terms);3. investigate the needs of the potential users to manage the more intensive irrigation system;4. investigate the feasibility of the proposed financing mechanisms, including how they can best be tailored to small-scale farmers and the institutional embedding required;5. map the upscaling potential of the package in Mozambique and other Arid and semi-Arid lands, considering hydrogeological, socio-economic, and institutional parameters, and develop the upscaling plan for the near future in collaboration with donors and financiers. The results will be recorded in an inception report, technical assessment report, business assessment report, short upscaling assessment report and a summary of the main findings, including a description of the way-forward, which in includes an evaluation on whether or not to implement a pilot.</narrative>
  </description>
